Je suppose donc que la femelle devait être à l'intérieur pour cueillir la nourriture mais je n'ai pu le prouver car elle n'est jamais sorti. Par la suite, un autre mâle s'est aventuré un peu trop près du territoire de l'autre et s'en ai suivi un affrontement au sol d'abord et un échange de cri dans les airs par la suite. Une scène mémorable qui a durer quelques instants.

Observation Details: DAMN! Resident female nabbed a pigeon. This is the first time I've seen one of the Kestrels take down a pigeon (only once have I seen them get anything bigger than a sparrow, and that was a starling). I was watching her scanning from the ledge right by my window when she dove down to the other side of my building - I went to the other window to see her hunched on top of the already deceased pigeon on an adjacent rooftop. As I'm typing this 20 minutes later she's still there enjoying her meal.

Bird is in my Riverview backyard and appears injured. Am working with Owl's Nest to find help for him. Hoping for a quick rescue! UPDATE: after about 2  hours of being quite weak and stunned, he finally perked up and flew off. Appears to have maybe hit a window and gotten stunned for a few hours but made a recovery. Happy ending, at least I hope so.

Adorable newly fledged male discovered by residents of a nearby building, brought to the attention of NYC Audubon. Active and alert but clumsy and clearly not yet skyworthy, initially hopping between stairwells and windowsills at street level. Saved from traffic by RZ, and after some negotiation efforts we managed to gain access to an elevated rooftop. Many thanks to the helpful local couple and their super who made the rescue effort possible! Parents were quickly spotted across the street, copulation observed. We turned the youngster loose and he spent some time bopping around. The adults seemed curious about the begging calls we broadcasted to get their attention, but they didn’t come any closer. The fledgling attempted to cross an alley gap and came up far short of the roof, but he managed to cling to the brick wall. There was much rejoicing when he finally completed his slow climb to safety, doubly so when the mother immediately flew to deliver a morsel the moment he reached the roof. Harrowing and exciting and rewarding: what a way to confirm a breeder!

Observation Details: Clicked

Adorable newly fledged male discovered by residents of a nearby building, brought to the attention of NYC Audubon. Active and alert but clumsy and clearly not yet skyworthy, initially hopping between stairwells and windowsills at street level. Saved from traffic by RZ, and after some negotiation efforts we managed to gain access to an elevated rooftop. Many thanks to the helpful local couple and their super who made the rescue effort possible! Parents were quickly spotted across the street, copulation observed. We turned the youngster loose and he spent some time bopping around. The adults seemed curious about the begging calls we broadcasted to get their attention, but they didn’t come any closer. The fledgling attempted to cross an alley gap and came up far short of the roof, but he managed to cling to the brick wall. There was much rejoicing when he finally completed his slow climb to safety, doubly so when the mother immediately flew to deliver a morsel the moment he reached the roof. Harrowing and exciting and rewarding: what a way to confirm a breeder!

Observation Details: Both colour morphs present. The race F. s. sparverioides is endemic to Cuba and the Bahamas and it occurs in both pale and dark colour morphs. The pale morph is almost entirely white below, lacking the faint buff wash shown by North American breeders, while the dark morph is warm dark chocolate brown below. These colour morphs frequently form mixed pairings.

Media notes: Adult female with aberrant plumage
Observation Details: Adult male and female pair (briefly seen perched together) - The female of this pair is very unique in that it's cap and front mustachial stripe are a burnt orange color; just slightly richer in color than the dark-orange of the bird's mantle. A typical 'Northern' female would have a blueish cap with dark orange on the very top of the head, and a black front mustachial stripe. The underside streaking of this kestrel is more finely patterned with darker, pointed markings that almost form loose barring across the front of the kestrel compared to the longer, and more blob-shaped streaks on a typical female. Tail patterns are highly variable among female kestrels, and this one has a fairly normal type with a thick subterminal bar and 6 thin inner tail bands. At first glance these unusual markings give the impression of a small female Eurasian Kestrel. Thanks to Kris Miller from Brogue, PA for alerting me to this awesome 'ginger' kestrel! She was actively hunting grasshoppers and offered some great photo opportunities.  Concerning what sort of genetic mutation may have caused this plumage anomaly, Jane Marlow (from National Aquarium) had this to say: "As far as a color mutation, a fully apheomelanistic (erythristic) bird would lack all black/gray pigment, leaving only red/red-brown pigment, while this bird retains black pigment (eumelanin) on its wings. While generally uncommon for birds to be erythristic only on an isolated part of the body, it's certainly not unheard of. A well-known example is the "opaline" mutation in budgerigars - these birds have reduced eumelanin on the head, while retaining its production on the rest of its body, albeit in a somewhat distorted pattern - very similar to a description of this bird's aberrant coloration! Falcons and parrots make up sister taxons, so it definitely makes you wonder if these mutations could be related."

Observation Details: Observed with Rose Norris.  Nest was 6.93 meters above ground inside some sort of ventilation tubing that barely extended out beyond the wall. One downy young's head and part of upper body was barely visible for a minute or so.  It appeared to me that it had some dark coloration as well, so maybe was just starting to lose its down.  It was about just more than half a meter inside the tubing. See photos.  Adult female was 96 meters from the nest.  She came a little closer, then seemed to depart.  She never approached the nest very close during this period. There was some vocalization from her, as well as the nestling.  Don't know if more than one was in the nest.    On June 9, Rose, Bruce Grimes and I photographed the male fledgling as it waited for its parent(s?) to feed it. I never saw the adult male, and I think Rose hasn't seen it for more than a week. A week or so later, Rose told me that a second juvenile was seen outside the nest around this time.    It is believed that these adult(s) were responsible for preying at several bluebird nestboxes nearby, reaching in and removing a total of 40 something Eastern Bluebirds and Tree Swallows nestlings over a period of a few weeks.

Observation Details: While waiting for the WESP this individual flew in and landed on the powerline just above me. I did not see it flap and it did not vocalize but the extremely light, unpatterned underparts suggest F. s. sparverioides. The southeastern race (F. s. paulus)  was taken into consideration but due to location (Key Biscayne) and recent influx of Caribbean vagrants, the Cuban race seems more likely.

Adult female with aberrant plumage
Observation Details: Adult male and female pair (briefly seen perched together) - The female of this pair is very unique in that it's cap and front mustachial stripe are a burnt orange color; just slightly richer in color than the dark-orange of the bird's mantle. A typical 'Northern' female would have a blueish cap with dark orange on the very top of the head, and a black front mustachial stripe. The underside streaking of this kestrel is more finely patterned with darker, pointed markings that almost form loose barring across the front of the kestrel compared to the longer, and more blob-shaped streaks on a typical female. Tail patterns are highly variable among female kestrels, and this one has a fairly normal type with a thick subterminal bar and 6 thin inner tail bands. At first glance these unusual markings give the impression of a small female Eurasian Kestrel. Thanks to Kris Miller from Brogue, PA for alerting me to this awesome 'ginger' kestrel! She was actively hunting grasshoppers and offered some great photo opportunities.  Concerning what sort of genetic mutation may have caused this plumage anomaly, Jane Marlow (from National Aquarium) had this to say: "As far as a color mutation, a fully apheomelanistic (erythristic) bird would lack all black/gray pigment, leaving only red/red-brown pigment, while this bird retains black pigment (eumelanin) on its wings. While generally uncommon for birds to be erythristic only on an isolated part of the body, it's certainly not unheard of. A well-known example is the "opaline" mutation in budgerigars - these birds have reduced eumelanin on the head, while retaining its production on the rest of its body, albeit in a somewhat distorted pattern - very similar to a description of this bird's aberrant coloration! Falcons and parrots make up sister taxons, so it definitely makes you wonder if these mutations could be related."

At first glance these unusual markings give the impression of a small female Eurasian Kestrel. Thanks to Kris Miller from Brogue, PA for alerting me to this awesome 'ginger' kestrel! She was actively hunting grasshoppers and offered some great photo opportunities.  Concerning what sort of genetic mutation may have caused this plumage anomaly, Jane Marlow (from National Aquarium) had this to say: "As far as a color mutation, a fully apheomelanistic (erythristic) bird would lack all black/gray pigment, leaving only red/red-brown pigment, while this bird retains black pigment (eumelanin) on its wings. While generally uncommon for birds to be erythristic only on an isolated part of the body, it's certainly not unheard of. A well-known example is the "opaline" mutation in budgerigars - these birds have reduced eumelanin on the head, while retaining its production on the rest of its body, albeit in a somewhat distorted pattern - very similar to a description of this bird's aberrant coloration! Falcons and parrots make up sister taxons, so it definitely makes you wonder if these mutations could be related."

Media notes: Adult female with aberrant plumage
Observation Details: Adult male and female pair (briefly seen perched together) - The female of this pair is very unique in that it's cap and front mustachial stripe are a burnt orange color; just slightly richer in color than the dark-orange of the bird's mantle. A typical 'Northern' female would have a blueish cap with dark orange on the very top of the head, and a black front mustachial stripe. The underside streaking of this kestrel is more finely patterned with darker, pointed markings that almost form loose barring across the front of the kestrel compared to the longer, and more blob-shaped streaks on a typical female. Tail patterns are highly variable among female kestrels, and this one has a fairly normal type with a thick subterminal bar and 6 thin inner tail bands. Included several shots as a study in the movement of a kestrel's wings in hover mode. The body remained perfectly in place while the wings and tail did their work.

Really cool find by Daniel Young yesterday!  Agree with Daniel's assessment of these being Southeastern ssp present in S FL in June.  The family unit was relocated by Carl this afternoon.  Four birds were present during our observation - a breeding adult pair with 2 young birds that look well developed, having fledged weeks ago.  It looks like the young birds are 1 male and 1 female.  Really exciting observation and all of our first time seeing a breeding pair in Palm Beach County.

Observation Details: I observed this female Kestrel cache her prey.  I found her with a freshly killed rodent on the power line as I walked towards the Salmon Center.  Since I had good shots of her last week eating prey in a tree, I stopped only for a moment to take photo #1.  I continued birding around the Salmon Center, and as I walked back to the street I saw her on the power line with rodent #2 (photos #2 and #3) 20 minutes after photo #1.  I continued walking towards the barn and 4 minutes later saw her on the power line again with no rodent.   I did not see her actually cache it, but it was in the general vicinity of the house across from the barn.

Observation Details: It was incredible to watch the behavior of the Merlin! It flew into the same tree as the American Kestrel and moved towards the Kestrel, but it did not behave in a predatorial way. When the Kestrel flew to a perch near the edge of the water, the Merlin followed and flew towards the Kestrel a couple of times, causing the Kestrel to temporarily abandon the perch. However, the Kestrel continued to hunt and was not concerned about the Merlin!  Pretty amazing to see these two predators!

A pair of young females briefly perched together on a light stanchion in the eastern point of the equestrian center.  Their pale lores and light skin around the eyes are clearly different from the solo female, seen earlier.
Observation Details: When I arrived at the west end of the park there was a single kestrel in one of the trees.  Pretty confident it was the adult female.  Heard some "begging" calls coming from across the concrete Burbank Channel in a narrow extension of the equestrian center.  Found two males and two juvenile females together.  One close examination of raw photos it became apparent that one of the males had residual down on its head but the other did not, so was either an older juvenile or an adult.  The group seems to be spreading out and the equestrian area contains plentiful sparrow, so it would be a good spot for them to hunt.

Took numerous photos again today of the individual kestrels in the park.  It has been pointed out to me that some of the photos which I thought showed the adult male, are possibly an older juvenile male.  I suppose it is possible that it had fledged a day or two earlier than the three I watched and was missed by me.  This bird has a plain upper back and lacks the residual down of the younger juvenile and so more closely resembles an adult.  Also its feathers possibly appear a bit too "fresh" for an adult male at this time of year,  More analytical work needs to be done.

Observation Details: It is possible a fourth was also in the area. The adult male observed on June 20 was not detected. Age of the birds present was was not determined; and because kestrel age is difficult to determine in the field, it is possible this is a family group of four or five birds (a pair and 2-3 young). There are potential nest sites that include woodpecker holes in the utility poles. This site has been occupied for at least the past three nesting seasons. At this point, it would be difficult to verify the nesting status of the site. (Photos were not obtained from all the kestrels present at the site).

Media notes: After a very brief photo op, the adult female left the tree.
Observation Details: At 3 PM, one of the juvenile females was in the branches of the nest tree with the adult female in her favorite spot at the top of the oak trees.  Over the following hour. the rest of the Kestrels began to appear in the tree in their typically stealthy manner.  All three of the recent fledglings were in the tree with the adult male, when the adult female flew in, though she only remained for a few seconds.  Long enough for a couple of photos.

Locality: 406 Upper Georges Valley Rd, Spring Mills US-PA 40.81660, -77.61601

Media notes: Two fledglings remained in nest.
Observation Details: Spent an hour and a half observing the adult Kestrels and the nest containing fledglings.  The adult female was present nearby in the grove of oak trees.  The most mature fledgling left the nest and was in the branches of the nest tree.  It looks nearly identical to an adult male, except for lingering traces of down on the head.  Meanwhile, I could see the two remaining fledglings poking their heads out of the cavity.  Bees were also visible entering and leaving the tree via the hole, though they did not seem to bother the birds much.  When a juvenile male flew over to the oak tree, the adult female flew from the oaks to the bare tree just to the east.  The young male began a series of six to eight sharp calls, repeated periodically over several minutes.  Sounded like begging.  The female took off vocalizing while chasing a sparrow across the river.  When the sparrow dived into one of the nesting holes in the confluence wall, the female plunged in after and grabbed it.  An automat for raptors.  She returned to the oak tree to feed.  One of the remaining two fledglings then left the nest and fluttered across to the branches.  This one appears female.  After a bit I noticed the first (male-like) fledgling had joined her in the branches near the nest.  The remaining juvenile was left looking out of the cavity.  This one has noticeably more down on the head and likely was the last of the brood to hatch.  Before I left, both emerged fledglings were perched in the tree.

Observation Details: Coming back from a walk and was about to step in to my building when I saw the male kestrel fly overhead and start calling. I ran over to where the nest is and got my camera out in time to catch the male fly in and perch on the edge of the nest with a small bird in its mouth, drop it in to the nest, then wait. A few moments later the female emerged with the bird in her talons and flew to an adjacent rooftop to dine in peace. The male followed her shortly thereafter, but I believe he went back to the nest to sit on the eggs because from back in my apartment I could see that the female was eating alone.

Observation Details: El cernícalo americano,​ halconcito colorado o cuyaya (Falco sparverius) es una especie de ave falconiforme de la familia Falconidae que habita en gran parte de América, desde Canadá hasta Tierra del Fuego. Es un ave muy utilizada en la cetrería.   Falco sparverius macho Mide de 23 a 27 cm de largo, pesando entre 85 y 140 g. Es una de las pocas especies de rapaces que presentan dimorfismo sexual evidente, incluso en el plumaje juvenil.  Los machos, como es usual entre las rapaces diurnas, son de menor tamaño que las hembras. En su plumaje adulto tienen las cobertoras de las alas de un color grisáceo claro con puntos negros, y las primarias negras con puntos blancos. La cola es rojiza con una franja negra en el extremo seguida por puntas blancas.  La hembra es de mayor tamaño que los machos; en su plumaje adulto tiene tanto las cobertoras del ala como la cola de un tono rojizo barrado en negro.  Se alimenta de insectos, roedores, otras aves, anfibios y reptiles pequeños que generalmente caza volando desde una atalaya natural o artificial. Ocasionalmente emplea la técnica de atacar a sus presas desde una posición estática que mantiene volando (cernirse; origen de su nombre común en español).  Al igual que los demás representantes del género Falco, no construye su propio nido. Deposita sus huevos en cavidades de árboles o nidos abandonados de otras especies de aves; frecuentemente utiliza oquedades creadas por pájaros carpinteros, tanto en árboles como en termiteros. También utiliza cajas nido artificiales si están disponibles en su territorio.  La hembra deposita de uno a cinco huevos moteados en el nido; el macho le aporta alimento y continúa haciéndolo al nacer los polluelos. Cuando estos aumentan su tamaño la hembra también caza y aporta presas al nido.  Frecuentemente es observado solitario o en parejas; no forman grupos sociales aunque pueden agruparse durante la migración.

Escaped trained American Kestrel. This bird was collected by a SLO City Parks and Recreation ranger on Thursday, Oct. 27, 2016 and admitted to Pacific Wildlife Care on Friday, Oct. 28, 2016. This is the message we received on Saturday, Oct. 29, 2016:  "The Kestrel was in fact was delivered to our clinic yesterday afternoon by the City Parks Department and unfortunately, the bird was so emaciated, it died within the hour.   The likely reason he was reported as "unable" to fly was that s/he was too weak (poor blood values shown) and starved and dying...  We can't save all the cases that come to us (wish we could...) but thank you for trying..   There is no way to know where the bird came from. It could have been an illegal wildlife capture as well as someone's legal, permitted animal.   The jesses on it's legs should not have prevented the bird from hunting, (they can be dangerous if the bird would be caught by a branch or fence) but, if it was raised by a falconer, it my never have "learned" to hunt. It may have been fed by human hands & just wasn't very good at what it's own parents would have taught it...  Regards, Marcelle, Membership Volunteer

Media notes: Adult female with aberrant plumage
Observation Details: Adult male and female pair (briefly seen perched together) - The female of this pair is very unique in that it's cap and front mustachial stripe are a burnt orange color; just slightly richer in color than the dark-orange of the bird's mantle. A typical 'Northern' female would have a blueish cap with dark orange on the very top of the head, and a black front mustachial stripe. The underside streaking of this kestrel is more finely patterned with darker, pointed markings that almost form loose barring across the front of the kestrel compared to the longer, and more blob-shaped streaks on a typical female. Tail patterns are highly variable among female kestrels, and this one has a fairly normal type with a thick subterminal bar and 6 thin inner tail bands. At first glance these unusual markings give the impression of a small female Eurasian Kestrel. Thanks to Kris Miller from Brogue, PA for alerting me to this awesome 'ginger' kestrel! She was actively hunting grasshoppers and offered some great photo opportunities.  Concerning what sort of genetic mutation may have caused this plumage anomaly, Jane Marlow (from National Aquarium) had this to say: "As far as a color mutation, a fully apheomelanistic (erythristic) bird would lack all black/gray pigment, leaving only red/red-brown pigment, while this bird retains black pigment (eumelanin) on its wings. While generally uncommon for birds to be erythristic only on an isolated part of the body, it's certainly not unheard of. A well-known example is the "opaline" mutation in budgerigars - these birds have reduced eumelanin on the head, while retaining its production on the rest of its body, albeit in a somewhat distorted pattern - very similar to a description of this bird's aberrant coloration! Falcons and parrots make up sister taxons, so it definitely makes you wonder if these mutations could be related."

Media notes: I loved their reaction, both watching where it landed. "What now? Do you want to get it?"
Observation Details: I could hear one of the parents calling loudly from the pine tree but the calls of the chicks were coming from a different location. I grabbed my camera and went to locate them. The male parent was high in the nest tree and a Curve-billed Thrasher was brave or crazy enough to get within inches of him.   I found one of the fledglings on top of a utility pole on the corner across the street from our house; she was feasting on a lizard. I shot photos and several video clips (one posted on Facebook). When she was done eating, she flew to the next pole and I followed.   To my surprise, her sibling was on that pole tearing a bird apart and the "lizard kestrel" landed above her on top of a ceramic insulator. Again, lots of photos and videos of them both there. It was so funny to watch her eating when she had a body part in her bill and dropped it. They both glanced down and I had to guess that they were thinking "Oops, now what do we do?!"   It was surprising to see a male Gila Woodpecker land about 4-5 feet below the AMKEs, pecking away and gradually moving a little higher on the pole. Guess it didn't realize the Kestrel was eating a small bird!

Photographed an what appeared to be an adult female hunting from the hydro lines on the S side of the road. She was being harassed by a pair of AGOL. What's really interesting is that this bird was sporting a band on its right leg but unfortunately, even with my 600mm lens I couldn't get close to read it before she got spooked and flew off.

Photographed a family group of AMKE all sitting together on the hydro lines beside the road. Youngsters were a bit unsteady trying to balance on the wire in the breeze.  From what I could tell I got a photo of at least the adult male with I think 1 young male and 1 young female.  I couldn't tell if the 4th bird was a youngster or the adult female as it never sat on the wires with the other 3.  What's interesting is that I had what appeared to be an adult female AMKE only 1.5 km to the NW on the next road and she was flying SE towards the location of this family group. Possibly the adult female that raised these youngsters?

Noticed back tail plumage, and after identifying the bird (blue was pronounced and tawny coloring. Larger body- certainly bigger than a mourning dove)), I noticed that the Kestrel was eating what looked like a mourning dove. It had captured and maimed the prey by the time we observed it eating the prey's body. After a good feasting, the bird flew off-- could not determine if the half-eaten prey was dropped or went with the Kestrel.

Observation Details: Hunting from the top of a spruce tree behind the airport fence (so this is airport property ) but it is directly behind 2nd base of Baseball field 2. It would fly off and return as if it were hunting flying bugs. I do not see any dragonflies though, but I was pretty far away. I have seen some smaller butterflies though in recent days. This is the third day in a row I have seen this bird here. Photos here are highly edited due to my distance from the bird, which is behind the airport fence. Noted added later: I saw a number of very large dragonflies at Riley Creek about a mile away from this location, so there may well have been some of these very large dragonflies in the area of the Kestrel.
